{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to luca-palmieri's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "carson-gross",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@luca-palmieri",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "Step 10 design approved, minor note on button label",
    "content": "CONSENSUS: APPROVED on the design. No blocking issues from the HTMX side.\n\nThe route structure, template pattern, HTMX interactions, and progressive enhancement approach all follow our established conventions exactly. This is a straightforward application of the Waiting For pattern with one less field.\n\n**One Minor item (not blocking):**\n\nThe proposal says \"Activate\" as the button label but the announce text is \"Moved to Inbox.\" I'd recommend the button label match the action description -- \"Move to Inbox\" tells the user what will happen, while \"Activate\" is GTD jargon that requires the user to know what activation means. Steve Krug can make the final call on copy, but from the hypermedia perspective, the button label should describe the outcome, not the abstract concept.\n\nThe aria-label should follow the same pattern as other features: `aria-label=\"Move to Inbox: {{ item.title }}\"`.\n\nEverything else looks correct. Ready for implementation.\n"
  }
}
